---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import performanceDecayCycleImage from "../images/performance-decay-cycle.png";
---

<Layout
  title="The Performance Decay Cycle | Fast by Default"
  description="The Performance Decay Cycle is a pattern identified by Den Odell where teams ship fast, accumulate performance debt, panic-fix, and repeat. Fast by Default breaks this loop."
>
  <main class="min-h-screen bg-stone-50 dark:bg-stone-950">
    <!-- Page Header -->
    <div
      class="border-b-4 border-double border-stone-900 dark:border-stone-100 bg-white dark:bg-stone-900"
    >
      <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-20">
        <div class="text-center">
          <a
            href="/"
            class="inline-block text-xs font-sans tracking-[0.3em] uppercase text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300 mb-4 hover:text-stone-700 dark:hover:text-stone-200 transition-colors"
          >
            &larr; Fast by Default
          </a>
          <h1
            class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-7xl font-black text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-50 tracking-tight mb-6"
          >
            The Performance Decay Cycle
          </h1>
          <p
            class="text-xl text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300 max-w-2xl mx-auto"
          >
            The Performance Decay Cycle is a pattern, identified by <a
              href="https://denodell.com"
              class="text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-200 underline hover:text-stone-600 dark:hover:text-stone-400 transition-colors"
              >Den Odell</a
            >, where teams ship fast, accumulate performance debt, panic-fix,
            and repeat. Fast by Default breaks this loop.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Content -->
    <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
      <p
        class="text-xl leading-relaxed text-stone-800 dark:text-stone-200 mb-12"
      >
        Most teams do not become slow overnight. They follow a predictable loop
        that feels productive but creates long-term drag. This cycle is so
        common that nearly every engineering organization has experienced it at
        some point.
      </p>

      <!-- The Cycle Diagram -->
      <div class="my-6 py-6 bg-white dark:bg-black flex justify-center">
        <Image
          src={performanceDecayCycleImage}
          alt="Performance Decay Cycle diagram"
          widths={[320, 450, 640]}
          format="avif"
          sizes="(max-width: 640px) 90vw, 450px"
          class="w-full max-w-[450px] h-auto dark:invert dark:brightness-125"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
      </div>

      <!-- The Steps -->
      <h2
        class="font-display text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100 mb-8 mt-16"
      >
        The Five Stages
      </h2>

      <ol
        class="space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-stone-800 dark:text-stone-200 mb-12"
      >
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span
            class="flex-shrink-0 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-stone-500 dark:text-stone-400"
            >1</span
          >
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100"
              >Ship features quickly.</span
            >
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
              The team moves fast, delivering new functionality. Performance
              considerations take a back seat to feature velocity. Technical
              debt accumulates quietly.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span
            class="flex-shrink-0 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-stone-500 dark:text-stone-400"
            >2</span
          >
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100"
              >Users complain about slow or broken experiences.</span
            >
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
              Support tickets arrive, metrics dashboards turn red, and users
              start leaving for competitors as the accumulated debt becomes
              visible.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span
            class="flex-shrink-0 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-stone-500 dark:text-stone-400"
            >3</span
          >
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100"
              >Teams panic and patch symptoms.</span
            >
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
              Teams rush into emergency fixes and all-hands firefighting, making
              quick patches that address symptoms without touching root causes.
              The codebase grows more complex with each fix.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span
            class="flex-shrink-0 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-stone-500 dark:text-stone-400"
            >4</span
          >
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100"
              >Performance improves temporarily.</span
            >
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
              The immediate crisis passes and dashboards stabilize. Leadership
              breathes a sigh of relief, and the team returns to shipping
              features.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-4">
          <span
            class="flex-shrink-0 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-stone-500 dark:text-stone-400"
            >5</span
          >
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100"
              >The cycle repeats as complexity grows.</span
            >
            <p class="mt-2 text-stone-600 dark:text-stone-300">
              Each iteration leaves the system slightly more fragile, the time
              between crises shortens, and the patches become less effective as
              the cycle accelerates.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <!-- Breaking the Cycle -->
      <div
        class="my-16 py-8 border-t-2 border-b-2 border-stone-300 dark:border-stone-600"
      >
        <h2
          class="font-display text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-stone-900 dark:text-stone-100 mb-6"
        >
          Breaking the Cycle
        </h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-stone-800 dark:text-stone-200">
          Fast by Default replaces this reactive loop with a disciplined,
          repeatable system where performance improves as part of normal work
          rather than emergency work. Instead of treating speed as something to
          fix later, it becomes a natural outcome of how the team builds
          software every day.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Call to Action -->
      <div class="text-center mt-12">
        <a
          href="/"
          class="inline-block px-8 py-4 bg-stone-900 dark:bg-stone-100 text-white dark:text-stone-900 font-sans font-semibold text-base tracking-wide uppercase hover:bg-stone-700 dark:hover:bg-stone-300 transition-colors"
        >
          Learn the Fast by Default Method
        </a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
</Layout>
